  "What are the three main stages of the Calvin cycle in order?": "",
  "Carbon fixation, reduction, regeneration of RuBP": "",
  "Glycolysis, Krebs cycle, ETC": "",
  "Oxidation, phosphorylation, reduction": "",
  "Reduction, fixation, regeneration": "",
  "The Calvin cycle has three stages: (1) carbon fixation (CO₂ + RuBP → 3-PGA via RuBisCO), (2) reduction (3-PGA → G3P using ATP and NADPH), and (3) regeneration of RuBP (using ATP to reform the CO₂ acceptor).": "",
  "To produce one molecule of glucose, how many CO₂ molecules must be fixed by the Calvin cycle?": "",
  "18": "",
  "Glucose is a 6-carbon molecule. Since each turn of the Calvin cycle fixes one CO₂, six turns are needed to produce two G3P molecules that combine to form one glucose (6 CO₂ → 12 G3P → 2 net G3P → 1 glucose).": "",
  "What happens to G3P molecules after they exit the Calvin cycle?": "",
  "They are immediately converted to CO₂": "",
  "They can be used to synthesize glucose, sucrose, starch, amino acids, and other organic molecules": "",
  "They are stored directly as ATP": "",
  "They return to the light reactions": "",
  "G3P is a versatile 3-carbon sugar that serves as the starting material for many biosynthetic pathways. Two G3P molecules can form glucose, which may be converted to sucrose for transport or starch for storage.": "",
