  "Cellular respiration, which occurs in the absence of light": "",
  "The light-independent reactions (Calvin cycle) do not directly use photons but rely on ATP and NADPH from the light reactions. The term can be misleading because these reactions mainly occur during the day when the light reactions supply their substrates.": "",
  "A plant breeder is developing wheat varieties for hot, dry climates where photorespiration significantly reduces crop yields. She considers introducing C4 carbon fixation traits into wheat (a C3 plant). Why would this reduce photorespiration?": "",
  "C4 carbon fixation concentrates CO₂ around RuBisCO in bundle sheath cells, so RuBisCO is more likely to fix CO₂ rather than O₂, reducing photorespiration": "",
  "C4 plants do not need the Calvin cycle, which is consistent with how photorespiration mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "C4 traits would eliminate RuBisCO from the plant entirely without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "C4 traits allow wheat to photosynthesize without water in most scenarios involving photorespiration factors": "",
  "C4 fixation uses PEP carboxylase to pre-fix CO₂ and concentrate it in bundle sheath cells where RuBisCO operates. The elevated CO₂ concentration favors carboxylation over oxygenation, dramatically reducing photorespiration.": "",
  "A scientist increases CO₂ levels in a growth chamber from 400 ppm to 800 ppm while keeping all other conditions constant for C3 plants. She observes an increase in photosynthetic rate. What explains this at the molecular level?": "",
  "Higher CO₂ directly increases the rate of the light reactions": "",
  "Higher CO₂ concentration increases RuBisCO's carboxylation rate and reduces its oxygenation rate, accelerating the Calvin cycle and net carbon fixation": "",
  "CO₂ replaces water as the electron donor in the light reactions": "",
  "CO₂ directly activates ATP synthase": "",
  "RuBisCO is not saturated at current atmospheric CO₂ levels. Doubling CO₂ increases the substrate concentration for carboxylation and competitively reduces oxygenation, boosting net photosynthetic rate in C3 plants.": "",
  "A desert ecologist studies cacti that open their stomata only at night. During the hottest part of the day, the stomata are tightly closed. How does this CAM strategy allow the cactus to photosynthesize while conserving water?": "",
  "The cactus stores light energy at night and uses it during the day, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these night dynamics operate": "",
  "The cactus performs the Calvin cycle at night using moonlight, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these night dynamics operate": "",
  "At night, open stomata allow CO₂ uptake and fixation into malic acid stored in vacuoles; during the day, stomata close to prevent water loss while malic acid is decarboxylated to release CO₂ for the Calvin cycle": "",
  "Cacti do not need CO₂ for photosynthesis, since the patterns governing night behavior generally combine with stomata conditions to create this type of result": "",
  "CAM plants temporally separate CO₂ fixation (night) from the Calvin cycle (day). Night fixation by PEP carboxylase stores carbon as malic acid. By day, closed stomata prevent water loss while stored acid releases CO₂ for the Calvin cycle.": "",
  "A researcher measures the ratio of CO₂ fixed to O₂ consumed by RuBisCO at different temperatures and finds that photorespiration increases dramatically above 30°C. What molecular property of RuBisCO explains this temperature dependence?": "",
  "At higher temperatures, O₂ solubility decreases less than CO₂ solubility, and RuBisCO's relative affinity for O₂ increases, favoring oxygenation over carboxylation": "",
  "High temperatures cause stomata to open wider, flooding cells with O₂, particularly in the context of Rubisco": "",
  "Temperature has no effect on RuBisCO's substrate specificity, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "RuBisCO denatures above 30°C when the interaction between Rubisco and increases factors is taken into full account": "",
  "At higher temperatures, the ratio of dissolved O₂ to CO₂ increases, and RuBisCO's specificity factor decreases, making oxygenation (photorespiration) more competitive. This is why C4 and CAM adaptations are advantageous in hot environments.": "",
  "An agricultural engineer is studying the effect of rising atmospheric CO₂ on global food production. She finds that C3 crops like rice and wheat show increased yields at elevated CO₂, but C4 crops like corn show minimal improvement. Why do C4 plants respond less to elevated CO₂?": "",
  "Elevated CO₂ is toxic to C4 plants, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing already dynamics": "",
