  "C4 plants do not use CO₂ in photosynthesis, which is consistent with how already mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "C4 plants cannot absorb CO₂ through their stomata in most scenarios involving already factors": "",
  "C4 plants already have a CO₂-concentrating mechanism that keeps RuBisCO nearly saturated with CO₂. Since RuBisCO is already working at near-maximum carboxylation capacity, additional atmospheric CO₂ has diminishing returns.": "",
  "A biochemist adds a competitive inhibitor of RuBisCO to isolated chloroplasts that are actively photosynthesizing. What immediate changes would she expect in the concentrations of Calvin cycle intermediates?": "",
  "All intermediates would increase equally": "",
  "Both RuBP and 3-PGA levels would increase": "",
  "G3P would accumulate because it cannot be used": "",
  "RuBP would accumulate (not being consumed), while 3-PGA and G3P levels would decrease (not being produced)": "",
  "Inhibiting RuBisCO blocks the conversion of RuBP + CO₂ → 3-PGA. RuBP continues to be regenerated but is not consumed, so it accumulates. 3-PGA is not produced, so it and downstream G3P decline.": "",
  "A climate scientist proposes using genetically enhanced trees with improved RuBisCO efficiency to increase global carbon sequestration and combat climate change. What aspect of RuBisCO makes this enzyme a promising target for bioengineering?": "",
  "RuBisCO is already highly efficient and cannot be improved": "",
  "RuBisCO is slow (only ~3-10 reactions/sec) and has a dual affinity for both CO₂ and O₂; improving its speed or CO₂ specificity could significantly increase carbon fixation efficiency": "",
  "RuBisCO does not play a significant role in the global carbon cycle": "",
  "RuBisCO is found only in C4 plants, limiting its application": "",
  "RuBisCO is remarkably slow and imprecise. It catalyzes only 3-10 reactions per second (compared to thousands for most enzymes) and wastefully fixes O₂ about 25% of the time. Engineering a faster, more CO₂-specific RuBisCO could dramatically improve photosynthetic efficiency.": "",
  "A student removes all light from a growing plant and supplies it with radioactively labeled CO₂ (¹⁴CO₂). After 24 hours in complete darkness, she finds no ¹⁴C incorporated into organic molecules. Why did carbon fixation fail even though CO₂ was available?": "",
  "Radioactive CO₂ cannot be fixed by RuBisCO without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Without light reactions, no ATP and NADPH are produced, so the Calvin cycle cannot operate even though CO₂ and RuBisCO are present": "",
  "RuBisCO is degraded in the dark in most scenarios involving light factors": "",
  "CO₂ cannot enter the leaf in the dark, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "The Calvin cycle requires ATP and NADPH from the light reactions for the reduction and regeneration phases. Without light, these energy carriers are depleted. Even though RuBisCO and CO₂ are present, the cycle stalls without its energy inputs.": "",
  "A marine ecologist discovers that phytoplankton in the Southern Ocean have RuBisCO variants with higher CO₂ specificity than land plants. She hypothesizes this is an adaptation to their environment. What environmental factor would favor higher CO₂ specificity in these organisms?": "",
  "Phytoplankton do not experience photorespiration": "",
  "RuBisCO specificity is unrelated to the environment": "",
  "Southern Ocean water is warm and has very high CO₂ levels": "",
  "Cold ocean water dissolves more O₂ relative to CO₂, increasing the O₂/CO₂ ratio around RuBisCO and making higher CO₂ specificity advantageous": "",
  "Cold water dissolves more gases, and O₂ is relatively more soluble than CO₂ at low temperatures. This increases the O₂/CO₂ ratio surrounding the phytoplankton, making a RuBisCO with higher CO₂ specificity advantageous to minimize photorespiration.": "",
  "A biotechnology company uses Melvin Calvin's classic experiment technique (the 'lollipop' experiment) with ¹⁴C-labeled CO₂ to trace the path of carbon in a new algal species. They expose algae to ¹⁴CO₂ for different time intervals and identify labeled compounds. After 5 seconds, only 3-PGA is heavily labeled. After 30 seconds, many labeled compounds appear including G3P and sugar phosphates. What does this time-course experiment reveal about the Calvin cycle?": "",
